Here's how to present a code example:

```markdown
## Code Highlights

### API Error Handling

All API calls use consistent error handling with 
user-friendly messages:

```typescript
export async function fetchUserRecipes(userId: string) {
  try {
    const response = await api.get(`/users/${userId}/recipes`);
    return { data: response.data, error: null };
  } catch (error) {
    if (error.response?.status === 404) {
      return { data: null, error: 'User not found' };
    }
    if (error.response?.status === 401) {
      return { data: null, error: 'Please log in to continue' };
    }
    return { data: null, error: 'Something went wrong. Please try again.' };
  }
}
```

This pattern is used across all 15+ API functions in 
the application.
```

**Why this works:**
- Brief context before the code
- Code is self-explanatory
- Comment after explains significance

```markdown
### Custom Hook: useDebounce

Search input uses debouncing to avoid excessive API calls:

```typescript
function useDebounce<T>(value: T, delay: number): T {
  const [debouncedValue, setDebouncedValue] = useState(value);

  useEffect(() => {
    const timer = setTimeout(() => {
      setDebouncedValue(value);
    }, delay);

    return () => clearTimeout(timer);
  }, [value, delay]);

  return debouncedValue;
}

// Usage in SearchBar component:
const [query, setQuery] = useState('');
const debouncedQuery = useDebounce(query, 300);

useEffect(() => {
  if (debouncedQuery) {
    searchRecipes(debouncedQuery);
  }
}, [debouncedQuery]);
```

This reduces API calls by 80% during active typing.
```

**Why this works:**
- Shows understanding of performance optimization
- Includes real usage example
- Quantifies the benefit (80% reduction)

Show growth and code quality awareness:

```markdown
### Refactoring: Recipe Filter Logic

**Before:** Nested conditionals that were hard to test

```javascript
// Hard to read, hard to test
function filterRecipes(recipes, filters) {
  return recipes.filter(recipe => {
    if (filters.cuisine && recipe.cuisine !== filters.cuisine) {
      return false;
    }
    if (filters.maxTime && recipe.time > filters.maxTime) {
      return false;
    }
    if (filters.difficulty && recipe.difficulty !== filters.difficulty) {
      return false;
    }
    return true;
  });
}
```

**After:** Composable filter functions

```javascript
// Each filter is testable independently
const filterByCuisine = (cuisine) => (recipe) => 
  !cuisine || recipe.cuisine === cuisine;

const filterByMaxTime = (maxTime) => (recipe) => 
  !maxTime || recipe.time <= maxTime;

const filterByDifficulty = (difficulty) => (recipe) => 
  !difficulty || recipe.difficulty === difficulty;

function filterRecipes(recipes, filters) {
  return recipes
    .filter(filterByCuisine(filters.cuisine))
    .filter(filterByMaxTime(filters.maxTime))
    .filter(filterByDifficulty(filters.difficulty));
}
```

This refactor made the code more testable and 
adding new filters trivial.
```

**Always specify the language for syntax highlighting:**

```markdown
```javascript    ‚Üê Good
const x = 1;
```

```               ‚Üê No highlighting
const x = 1;
```
```

**Supported languages:** javascript, typescript, python, jsx, tsx, sql, bash, json, css, html, and more.

**Add brief comments for context:**
```javascript
// Validates user input before saving to database
const validateRecipe = (data) => {
  // ... code
};
```

**Don't over-comment:**
```javascript
// This is bad - comments state the obvious
const x = 1; // sets x to 1
const y = x + 1; // adds 1 to x
```

**Comment the "why," not the "what":**
```javascript
// Use Math.floor to ensure integer result for pagination
const pageCount = Math.floor(total / pageSize);
```
